# LF in the repository on every platform — load-bearing, not cosmetic.
#
# Git for Windows defaults to `core.autocrlf=true`, which rewrites text files
# to CRLF on checkout. Identical content then has different BYTES on the two
# machines, which silently breaks every byte-comparison gate in this ecosystem
# (sweep's `content_hash`, hash ledgers, golden renders, byte-identical replay)
# — the gate fails on Windows for a reason that has nothing to do with the
# change under test, or worse, a hash-keyed cache quietly misses forever.
#
# `text=auto` still lets each working tree use its native endings; only what
# git STORES is normalized. Binary files are auto-detected and left alone.
* text=auto eol=lf

# Shell entry points must stay LF even if a tool would guess otherwise: a
# CRLF shebang line makes the kernel look for an interpreter named "bash\r"
# and fail with a bare, unexplained "command not found".
verify text eol=lf
*.sh text eol=lf
